 Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Barrons","meanings":["English: variant of   Barron  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Baron","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355925,"age":19,"year":"1603","julianDay":2306544,"description":"Accession of James I. Surrender of Hugh O'Neill. Enforcement of English Law in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Barron was born in 1584, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland. He married Margaret Calthorpe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1638, in Welton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1584–1638":"1584–1638","1569–Female":"1569–Surnud","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","13 January 1620":"13. jaanuar 1620","1584":"1584","1638":"1638","1603":"1603","Welton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Welton, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1584–1638":"1584–1638","1569–Female":"1569–Kuollut","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","13 January 1620":"13. tammikuuta 1620","1584":"1584","1638":"1638","1603":"1603","Welton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Welton, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irlanti","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1584–1638":"1584–1638","1569–Female":"1569–Décédée","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569":"1569","1600":"1600","1620":"1620","13 January 1620":"13 janvier 1620","1584":"1584","1638":"1638","1603":"1603","Welton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Welton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Cork, County Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Irlande","Welton, Northamptonshire, E